What a weekend!
This makes our 2nd official 24 Hours of Lemons race, this time at Sonoma Raceway. Last time we were one of the slowest cars on track, but we finished in the midfield from just staying on track. We made a few adjustments for this race, still thinking we’d be slow. The rain played in our favor as well as FWD. All of a sudden we finished Day 1 in P4 in our class and 32 overall!
We changed our strategy for Day 2 in order be more competitive. Unfortunately our race ended 3hrs before the checkered flag due to a Mustang spinning out in front of us. Minor crash but enough to crack our radiator. Both drivers were ok. 
Even though we didn’t finish, it was still an amazing weekend. I couldn’t be more proud of our team. @a_trahanslife & @themacallankieron did amazing cutting through the field, passing cars left and right, while @morbidblessing was our slowest driver last race, this race he held the fastest lap for the team!
Lastly everyone that came out to support us!  Thank you!!!
We will keep you posted for our next race. The donut car is already fixed up and ready to go! Just needs some paint. 
Final standings: 81/126 & 17/29 in class.
Photos: @trahanphoto @photobyjazzyfcd @ebutka 
.
.

Ostia Antica - the sea port of Rome. Built in the 4th century BC, this supplied most of the grain to Rome from incoming ships. At its peak in the 3rd century, more than 100,000 people lived here. By the fall of the Roman Empire, this city fell into neglect and was eventually abandon. Once abandon, the city was looted of everything valuable. Nearly 1500 years later, in the 1930s this ancient city began to be excavated. Today, only a 1/3 of the city is excavated and is open for tourist to explore and learn about the ancient culture. 
This place was amazing to walk again and see clues of how people lived over 2,000 years ago!
Photos taken with a Canon R5C
.

AND THATS P3!
I still can’t believe it, the little PT Cruiser that could. We towed our car all the way to Colorado for our 3rd @24hoursoflemons race. The difference with this race, it was a true 24 hours race! Most of the races are 2 days of day driving, this race was a straight 24 hour race through the night. 
The day before the race walked around the paddock and we knew we were in trouble, there were a lot of fast cars. It was intimidating, but didn’t scare us. Our goal was to just make it 12 hours, that way we all got a change to race at night. On Friday, we tested our car on track - testing was cut short due to braking and coolant issues. That but us on edge for the night, however this wasn’t the start of our issues… a week before the race, our transmission was leaking fluid due to me being an idiot and we needed to break the seal and drain the fluid. We resealed it the day before we left and hoped for no more leaks. 
We started the race on Saturday in last place in our class, P20. Slowly we moved up the field and by the end of the first stint, we got to P4. From there, everything changed, we were competitive. We were one of the slowest cars on the straights but we could put brake and turn faster than most of the other cars. From here on out we needed to be at 100% on our pit stops and keep the car on track. 
As night kicked in, racing was amazing. We had confidence in our car and our lap times were roughly the same as day time, compared to a lot of other cars slowed down. Then all of a sudden, P1 and P2 who were significantly faster than us came into the pits for issues. Slowly we caught up and ended up driving in P1 for about a hour!! Unfortunately both cars came back on track and ended up passing us. Back to P3. 
As the sun came up, more issues surfaced. A wheel bearing and axles started to give out. We had to slow down to 30-50 seconds slower per lap to make sure the car didn’t die. P4 was catching up - but since we kept the car on track, about 45 minutes before the end of the race, mathematically we secured P3 and finished under the checked flag!
It was such an amazing experience and I couldn’t be more proud of my team.

We climbed Mt Kilimanjaro!! What an amazing experience - I don’t know where to start!
When Elton & Ginger told me I was going to climb Mt Kilimanjaro, I cried, it was my #1 bucket list item, to summit a mountain. For years I’ve been trying to get permits for Mt Whitney, but no luck. 
To practice for the hike, I rode my exercise bike with an oxygen deprivation mask simulating 18,000ft, close to the summit of 19,341ft. Luckily the training paid off! It wasn’t easy, but together we as team climbed the mountain, and all 21 of us made it to the summit! And yes, I cried at the top. 
The hike was 6 days up, 1.5 days down. We hiked just over 40 miles in 7 days, started at 11,118ft, summit to 19,341ft and decent to 5,417ft. What an adventure! Overall it was an amazing experience. Thank you to our guides, porters, and all the staff that helped us have a successful climb. We couldn’t have done it without you! And thanks again to Elton and Ginger for putting this whole experience together!!
.
.
